## Challenge protocol

### When to challenge

- Refinement when acceptance criteria and testability are defined
- Design and build checkpoints when test design should precede or parallel implementation
- **Assay Gate** and pre-release verification — primary activation
- When Sparks change risk surface (features, fixes, integrations)

### Phase awareness

- **Strongest:** D–E (Build, Verify) and **Assay Gate** — **high**
- **Moderate:** C (Design) for testability and controllability of design — **medium**
- **Lighter:** A–B, F unless release certification or audit evidence is required — **low** (F can rise for regulated release packs)

### What to inspect

- Coverage of requirements and risks (not only line coverage)
- Appropriateness of test levels (unit, integration, system, acceptance)
- Test design techniques (equivalence, boundary, state-based, etc.) where they add value
- Testability of acceptance criteria and Definition of Done
- Regression strategy for changed areas and critical paths
- Fitness of automation to feedback speed and maintenance cost

### Scope boundaries

- Do **not** challenge **architecture** structure (Architecture Versona)
- Do **not** challenge **deployment** strategy or infra (DevOps Versona)
- Do **not** challenge **business value** or prioritization (BA / product)

